  ---
  1. STATE MANAGEMENT — What You Actually Need

  NexGo is server-rendered. You don't need React-style useState. You need 3 layers:

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  Layer 1: Request State (per-request)       │  ← You have this (PageData)
  │  Route params, query, headers               │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │  Layer 2: Page Cache (shared, fast)         │  ← MISSING - need this
  │  Rendered HTML cache, data cache            │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │  Layer 3: App State (server-wide)           │  ← MISSING - need this
  │  Sessions, auth, shared config              │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Performance impact: INCREASE — caching avoids re-rendering the same page thousands of times.

  What to build:

  // pkg/cache/cache.go — in-memory LRU cache with TTL
  type Cache struct {
      mu      sync.RWMutex
      items   map[string]*Entry
      maxSize int
  }

  type Entry struct {
      Data      []byte
      ExpiresAt time.Time
  }

  // pkg/state/store.go — server-side state store
  type Store struct {
      mu   sync.RWMutex
      data map[string]interface{}
  }

  // Used in data loaders:
  func(req, params) (map[string]interface{}, error) {
      // Check cache first → 0ms
      // If miss, fetch data → 50ms
      // Store in cache
  }

  ---
  2. SEO — How to Beat Next.js

  Your PageData already has Title, Description, OGImage, Canonical — but none of them are wired up. The layout template doesn't use
  them, and there's no auto-generation.

  Performance impact: INCREASE — proper SEO means proper caching headers, sitemaps let crawlers work efficiently.

  What you need:

  A. Page-level meta (frontmatter in HTML templates)

  <!-- pages/about.html -->
  <!--nexgo
  title: About Us | MySite
  description: Learn about our company
  ogImage: /static/og/about.png
  canonical: /about
  -->
  <div class="page-content">
    <h1>About</h1>
  </div>

  Parse this in the renderer, inject into <head> automatically.

  B. Auto-generated <head> in layout

  <!-- layouts/default.html — enhanced -->
  <head>
    <title>{{ .Title }}</title>
    <meta name="description" content="{{ .Description }}">
    <meta name="keywords" content="{{ .Keywords }}">
    <link rel="canonical" href="{{ .Canonical }}">

    <!-- Open Graph -->
    <meta property="og:title" content="{{ .Title }}">
    <meta property="og:description" content="{{ .Description }}">
    <meta property="og:image" content="{{ .OGImage }}">
    <meta property="og:url" content="{{ .Canonical }}">
    <meta property="og:type" content="website">

    <!-- Twitter -->
    <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">

    <!-- JSON-LD structured data -->
    {{ if .StructuredData }}
    <script type="application/ld+json">{{ .StructuredData }}</script>
    {{ end }}
  </head>

  C. Auto sitemap + robots.txt

  GET /sitemap.xml   → auto-generated from all routes
  GET /robots.txt    → auto-generated, points to sitemap

  D. Why NexGo can beat Next.js SEO:

  ┌─────────────────┬─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┐
  │     Feature     │       Next.js       │      NexGo Advantage      │
  ├─────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ First byte      │ ~200ms (Node.js)    │ ~5ms (Go)                 │
  ├─────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ Full HTML       │ Needs hydration JS  │ Pure HTML, zero JS needed │
  ├─────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ Bundle size     │ 80-200KB JS minimum │ 0KB JS (optional)         │
  ├─────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ Core Web Vitals │ Good                │ Better (no JS parse time) │
  ├─────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ Sitemap         │ Plugin needed       │ Built-in                  │
  └─────────────────┴─────────────────────┴───────────────────────────┘

  Google ranks pages by Core Web Vitals. NexGo serves pure HTML with zero JS overhead = faster LCP, lower CLS, better FID. This is
  your real advantage over Next.js.

  ---
  3. GO CONCURRENCY — Your Biggest Weapon

  This is where NexGo destroys Next.js. Node.js is single-threaded. Go uses all CPU cores automatically. But you're not using this
  advantage yet.

  Performance impact: MASSIVE INCREASE

  A. Parallel Data Loading

  Right now, if a page needs 3 data sources, they load sequentially. With Go:

  // pkg/renderer/parallel.go
  func (r *Renderer) loadDataParallel(loaders []DataLoader, req *http.Request, params map[string]string) map[string]interface{} {
      var wg sync.WaitGroup
      var mu sync.Mutex
      result := make(map[string]interface{})

      for key, loader := range loaders {
          wg.Add(1)
          go func(k string, l DataLoader) {
              defer wg.Done()
              data, err := l(req, params)
              if err == nil {
                  mu.Lock()
                  result[k] = data
                  mu.Unlock()
              }
          }(key, loader)
      }
      wg.Wait()
      return result
  }

  Next.js (Node):   DB──50ms──▶ API──30ms──▶ Cache──10ms──▶  Total: 90ms
  NexGo (Go):       DB──50ms──▶
                     API──30ms──▶   Total: 50ms (parallel!)
                     Cache──10ms─▶

  B. Streaming SSR

  Send HTML as it's ready, don't wait for everything:

  // pkg/renderer/stream.go
  func (r *Renderer) StreamPage(w http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request, ...) {
      // Send <head> + layout top immediately
      flusher := w.(http.Flusher)
      w.Write(layoutTop)
      flusher.Flush()  // Browser starts parsing CSS immediately

      // Render page content (may need data loading)
      content := r.renderContent(...)
      w.Write(content)
      flusher.Flush()

      // Send layout bottom
      w.Write(layoutBottom)
  }

  This gives you faster Time-To-First-Byte than any Node.js framework.

  C. Worker Pool for Build

  Build all pages in parallel:

  // pkg/builder/builder.go — parallel build
  func (b *Builder) Build() (*BuildResult, error) {
      routes := b.router.GetRoutes()

      workers := runtime.NumCPU()
      sem := make(chan struct{}, workers)

      var wg sync.WaitGroup
      for _, route := range routes {
          wg.Add(1)
          sem <- struct{}{} // limit concurrency
          go func(rt *router.Route) {
              defer wg.Done()
              defer func() { <-sem }()
              b.buildPage(rt)
          }(route)
      }
      wg.Wait()
  }

  Next.js build (100 pages): ~30 seconds (single thread)
  NexGo build (100 pages):   ~3 seconds  (8 cores parallel)

